{"version": "0.3.1", "atoms": [], "cards": [["code", {"code": "public interface Collection<T> {
 boolean isEmpty();
 int getSize();
}"}], ["code", {"code": "if (collection.getSize() == 0)"}], ["code", {"code": "if (collection.isEmpty())"}], ["code", {"code": "public final class Collections {
 public static <T> boolean isEmpty(Collection<T> c) {
 return c.getSize() != 0;
 }
}"}], ["code", {"code": "if (Collections.isEmpty(collection))"}], ["hr", {}]], "markups": [["em"], ["strong"]], "sections": [[1, "p", [[0, [1], 1, "TL;DR:"], [0, [], 0, " Keep your APIs as minimal as possible."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "API design is hard. But this is arguably the best tip I can give. Don’t add bells and whistles, let the clients do that themselves."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "This is a programming language agnostic concept, but I’ll be using Java to demonstrate my point."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "In my experience, interface creation often leads to the most existential debates I have with myself."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "For example:"]]], [10, 0], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "One of these methods is redundant. Is an "], [0, [1], 1, "isEmpty "], [0, [], 0, "method really necessary here when one can write:"]]], [10, 1], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "instead of:"]]], [10, 2], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "There are two valid reasons to add keep the isEmpty method:"]]], [3, "ol", [[[0, [], 0, "You’re just being extra nice to your clients by helping them keep the code simple to read and write."]], [[0, [], 0, "You want to make some distinct guarantees about the semantics or complexity of each method."]]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "I’ll just say that #1 is invalid. First, forget about making the code simple to write, it will probably be read far more often than it’s written. Second, making it simple to read without adding extra burden to those that are implementing your interface is silly. You can simply offer a static utility class that will never change:"]]], [10, 3], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Now the code is as simple as:"]]], [10, 4], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "#2, on the other hand, is rather valid if your interface wants to make some guarantees. For example, perhaps "], [0, [1], 1, "isEmpty()"], [0, [], 0, " is guaranteed to be a constant operation while "], [0, [1], 1, "getSize()"], [0, [], 0, " may not be. This is valid, but must be documented and explained to your users, potentially increasing complexity."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Such a debate raged long ago regarding the size() and empty() methods of C++’s Standard Template Library (STL). For what it’s worth, most standard containers support both."]]], [10, 5], [1, "h2", [[0, [], 0, "Accessibility"]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Whenever you find yourself exposing a method or field that is not private (including package-private), you are essentially stating that you plan to support the functionality for the foreseeable future. That will only make refactoring harder, leaving you with a clunky API."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "When you work on versioned software that is statically shipped to your clients (e.g., an SDK of some form) you learn some very hard lessons very quickly. Every single change to a public API that you make is a burden to your clients to upgrading."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "If you ever find yourself in an existential debate where you are attempting to predict the future on how a client will use a particular API, step back and ask yourself if it’s really necessary. Do not simply implement what you "], [0, [0], 1, "think"], [0, [], 0, " they "], [0, [0], 1, "might"], [0, [], 0, " need. Only add what you "], [0, [0], 1, "know"], [0, [], 0, " they "], [0, [0], 1, "will"], [0, [], 0, " need."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Deprecating or obsoleting functionality is at least an order of magnitude harder than creating it in the first place when you know it’s needed. Especially when you cannot be certain how your clients are using the code."], [0, [], 0, "
"], [0, [], 0, "
"]]]]}

{"version": "0.3.1", "atoms": [["soft-return", "", {}]], "cards": [["code", {"code": "“Contacts”: [{
  “Emails”: [“davidbyttow@example.com”], 
  “PhoneNumbers”: [“+15550001234”]
}]"}], ["code", {"code": "“Contacts”: [{
  “Emails”: [“sTYVRpsNfoluk5nQzoTnhu2AyW0=”], 
  “PhoneNumbers”: [“ga7tSDlB0s45nUKnmn9XERVTBqE=”]
}]"}], ["hr", {}]], "markups": [["em"], ["strong"], ["a", ["href", "http://mclov.in/2012/02/08/path-uploads-your-entire-address-book-to-their-servers.html"]], ["a", ["href", "http://twitter.com/davidbyttow"]], ["a", ["href", "http://twitter.com/dpup"]]], "sections": [[1, "h3", [[0, [], 0, "Users: Don’t be so trusting."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [0], 1, "“SomeNewApp would like to access your contacts.”"]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "If you’re like most people, you’ll press “OK” without even blinking an eye. If you’re a developer, then you’re probably a bit more cautious."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Because, after you click “OK”, what happens? Well, that depends."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [1], 1, "These days, anyone can throw an app together and publish it to the AppStore."], [0, [], 0, " And while Apple has a fairly stringent review process, they can only review what happens on the device, not what happens with the data that leaves the device."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Most of us remember the "], [0, [2], 1, "Path incident"], [0, [], 0, ". Though, this was a bit more devious in that it never asked for your permission (Apple since fixed this bug)."]]], [1, "blockquote", [[0, [], 0, "We upload the address book to our servers in order to help the user find and connect to their friends and family on Path quickly and effeciently as well as to notify them when friends and family join Path. Nothing more. —Dave Morin"]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Morin’s response is technically accurate, they upload the contact book to connect the user with their friends. Do they store the data? Probably, as they have to in order to match new friends that join the service long after you’ve uploaded your address book. But, even if a service doesn’t store them in a database, there are all sorts of other places it can go, such as into the logs that nearly all services keep for debug and analytical purposes. The data is there and it’s discoverable."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [1], 1, "That approach is wrong."], [0, [], 0, " You don’t need to upload phone numbers and email addresses, just a representation of them. Most developers believe that sending email addresses and phone numbers over SSL and storing them securely on the server is good enough. It’s not."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "The number of services that have contact data for millions of people (journalists, celebrities, politicians, etc) is probably quite staggering. "], [0, [1], 1, "Don’t be that service."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "You should only collect email address and phone number if users willingly give it to you. If you need to match them with their friends that sign up later, only collect and store contact details in a way that is matchable, but irrecoverable."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [1], 1, "Here’s the right way."], [0, [], 0, " Simply one-way obfuscate (e.g., hash, SHA1) any piece of personally identifiable information (email, phone number, etc) for each contact and store that. Use a little salt too. Then, when it comes time to match, do it on the obfuscated keys. At this point, you don’t even need to care if it’s an email address, phone number because it’s just an opaque blob. "], [0, [0], 1, "Disclaimer:"], [0, [], 0, " This is not meant to prevent against hacking attacks, as hashing (especially phone numbers) is easily defeated."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "A fine solution is to do this on the server, but the "], [0, [0], 1, "best"], [0, [], 0, " solution is to do it on the client before sending up the data. That way, you can make the guarantee to your users that their contact data never leaves their phone."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Also, just because you send data over SSL doesn’t mean you’re in the clear. Savvy people will inspect your traffic with a simple MITM proxy and check out what you’re doing. So instead of seeing this:"]]], [10, 0], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "They only see this:"]]], [10, 1], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Unfortunately, now you can’t get Kanye West’s phone number because one of his bodyguards signed up for your service. Sorry! :-("]]], [10, 2], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Follow me "], [0, [3], 1, "@davidbyttow"], [0, [], 0, "."]]], [1, "p", [[0, [], 0, "Special thanks to "], [0, [4], 1, "Dan Pupius"], [0, [], 0, " for making me realize the importance of this practice."], [0, [], 0, "
"], [0, [], 0, "
"]]]]}
